{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945101801/0580.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL\nTrippi, Georgia\u2019s Grid Star,\nOut of Army On 41 Points\nPolitical Pressure Charged in Early Release Army\nSays New Rule Made It Possible\nTampa. Fla Oct. 12\u2014(AP)--Staff\nSerst Charlie Trippi. the former Uni\nversity of Georgia Kose howl star,\nwas released from the army tonight\non 41 points\nThe backfield ace. whose release\nbrought protests from Tampa's news\npapers and charges that Georgia pol\niticians had brought pressure on the\nwar department, left Drew field with\nout any statement as to his immedi\nate attentions.\nIt was reported at the field, how\never. that he would report at once\nto the University of Georgia as a\nstudent. That will make him eligible\ntor the Georgia football team.\nIn Washington, the war department\nannounced that Trippi was being dis\ncharged from the air forces because\nhis commanding officer here had de\nclared him surplus.\nThe department said an armj or\nder, made public Saturday, made\nSergt Trippi eligible for discharge.\nThe order, applying to air. ground\nand service, forces, allows command\ners to discharge soldiers who are:\n1. Not currently eligible for dis\ncharge by reason of points or age.\n(Trippi has 11 points to his credit.)\n2. Not qualified for foreign duty\nand have completed two years of\nservice since September 16. 1940.\n3. Surplus to the requirements of\nthe force to which they were as\nsigned and \"not economically retrain\nable to perform useful service.\"\n4. Not possessed of a \"scarce skill\"\nneeded by the army.\nTrippi left the University of Geor\ngia after his sophomore year, follow\ning Georgias triumph over UCLA 9\nto 0 in the Rose bowl January 1. 1943.\nLast season while playing with the\n3d air force Gremlins, he was named\nto the Associated Press AU-Americsf\nservice team.\nThe Tampa Tribune declared that.\n\"It Is understood in football circles\nthat highest political pressure in\nGeorgia was brought to bear on the\nwar department to gain the stars\nrelease.\"\nAnd the Tampa Tisses asserted. I\n\u2018The wrath of millions of Gls who\nwould like to get out of the army but\ncan't under the point system should\nfall on the shoulders of the war de\npartment.\n\u2018\u2018Obviously the place to blame is the\nwar department which no doubt has\nlistened carefully to the demands of\nGeorgia politicians who are powerful\nin Congress and who want to have a\nbowl football team this \u2014not next\nyear,\" the Times continued editorially.\nGOVERNMENT BACK\nSEIZING MEAT TO\nFEED EUROPEANS\nAction Taken Because Amer\nican Public Buys So Heav\nily Uncle Sam Can t Meet\nCommitments\nWashington, Oct. 11\u2014(AP) \u2014Amer-\nicane bought more meat under the\nrecently liberalized rationing program\nthan had been expected, so the govern\nment went back to mandatory requisi\ntions today to get meat for shipment\nto Britain, France and other coun\ntriee.\nThe net effect is expected to be a\nlittle less meat for the average\ndomestic consumer than he has been\nbuying since the Ist. but officials\nsay he etill should get the amount\nthey figured for him in the first place\n\u2014a consumption rate of 148 pounds\nper year for the la\u00abt quarter of 1945.\nWants Half-Billion Pounds\nWhat the government wants is\n50(1,000,000 to 000.000,000 pounds for\nforeign consumption, which comes out\nto a little over a pound per month per\nAmerican.\nAverage consumption of about 150\npounds of meat last year set an\nAmerican record. Short supplies and\nmilitary and foreign needs cut the\ncivilian allocation in the summer of\n1945 to a rate of about 115 pounds\na year.\nSince ration point values were cut\nthe first of this month, officials\nfigure United States civilians have\nbeen pointing toward another con\nsumption record, and they say the\nsupply wouldn't stand it. The govern\nment set-asides were suspended short\nly after V-J day. Officials said they\nwill be suspended again when the\ndelating commitments are met.\nBuying In open competition with\ncivilians, the government has been\nunable to obtain meat pounds sought'\nfor commercial export.\nThus it took steps to require\nslaughterers to divert a sufficient\namount from civilian distribution\nchannels to fill export commitments.\nNEXT JULY SEEN\nCONTROL DEADLINE;\nOPA Chief Says 41 Per\nCent of 1400 Businessmen\nQuizzed Would End Price\nControl by That Time\nWashington. Oct. 12 \u2014(API\u2014 OPA\nAdministrator Cheater Bowles said to\nday that 41 per cent of more than\n1400 businessmen favor dropping al!\nprice control* by next July at the\nlatest.\nBowlea announced this in report\ning preliminary results of a survey\nof 7800 industry leaders to determine\ntheir opinions as to when price ceil\nings safely can be discontinued.\nReplies from 1436 have been tabu\nlated. Six per cent favored dropping\nceilings immediately. Another 8 per\ncent specified January 1.\nTwenty-nine per cent said not all\ncontrols should lie dropped before\nJuly 1. while 39 per cent were in\nfavor of a later date or of waiting\nuntil supply and demand are in bal\nance and wages have been stabilized.\nThe remaining 20 per cent returned\nthe questionnaire but did not an\nswer it.\nCiting replies from four major In\ndustries. OPA said that in the textile\nfield 34 per cent favored ending con\ntrols now or by January 1, and 65\nper cent at some later date clothing.\n31 per cent now or by January. Bl\nper cent later; food. 37 per cent now\nOr by January BO per cent later;\nbuilding material and construction.\nJS per cent now or by January, 62\nper cent later.\nCANADA MLASHES TAXES\nOttawa. Oct. 12\u2014(AP)\u2014 The Cana\ndian government tonight announced\na 1\u00ab per cent reduction In the per\nsonal Income tax along with other\nslashes In the wartime tax structure\namounting to >300,000,000 a year.\n6\nBIG HIGHWAY PLAN\nSTARTS THIS FALL\nTHROUGHOUT U.S. A.\nFederal Government and\nStates to Spend Billion An\nnually On 34,000-Milc Net\nwork, and Other Roads\nWashington. Oct. 13\u2014(A Pi\u2014The\nnation\u2019s greatest highway construc\ntion program gets going this fall.\nCongress stepped on the starter\nwhen it released federal funds\namounting to $500.000,00\u201c a year for\nthe next three years. These funds,\nprovided by the postwar highway act\nof 1944. will be matched by the states.\nBesides this three-year $3,500,000,000\nfederal-states project, an estimated\n$1,500,000,000 will be spent yearly on\ncounty roads and city streets outside\nth federal-aid system.\nThe record-breaking three-year ex\npenditure will be only the beginning\nof an expected 10 to 15-y%ar program\nof motor road expansion and improve\nment designed to meet traffic needs 20\nyears from now. It will provide:\n1. A 34,000 to 40,000-mile master\nnetwork of interstate highways, con\nnecting all the principal metropolitan\nareas and containing many new di\nvided multiple-lane expressways.\n2. A greatly improved system of\nsecondary, or farm-to-market, high\nways.\n3. Elimination nf traffic bottlenecks\nin and near cities\u2014now the nation\u2019s\nbiggest obstacle to safe and economic\nmotor travel.\n34.000-Mile Network\nRoutes on the interstate system\nwill closely follow' a 34.000-mile net\nwor\u00df recommended after three years\nof study by a committee of federal\nand state highway experts. It con\nnects directly all cities of 30,000 or\nmore population and it reaches 59 of\nthe 63 cities between 100.000 and\n300.000. It passes through the most\npopulous belts of rural and small\ntown population and lidks most of\nthe country\u2019s industrial centers.\nThe great bulk of the interstate\nnetwmrk is comprised of established\nroutes. Many of these routes, how\never. are now narrow two-lane roads.\nSome are battered from wartime\ntruck travel. They will be widened\nand otherwise improved to \"provide\nbuilt-in safety and high traffic\ncapacity.\u201d\nAlthough the network contains\nonly slightly more than 1 per cent\nof the 3.267,00 miles of roads a.nd\nstreets in the United States, it car\nries 20 per cent of the total traffic.\nCompletely Modern\nDesign standards are the highest\never adopted by the American As\nsociation of state highway officials.\nHeavily-traveled sections of the net\nwork w ill be more modern than the\nPennsylvania turnpike, famous su\nperhighway extending from near\nHarrisburg to near Pittsburg.\nDivided multiple-lane highways\nwill be eliminated.\nThere will he a minimum of inter\nsections and stop signs. Efforts will\nbe made to eliminate all road and\nrailroad grade crossings where 3000\nvehicles per hour must be handled.\nAccess to many stretches of road\nwill be limited. In urban sections\nof the interstate system, all surfac\ning and pavement will be designed\nfor 12-foot lanes.\n\u201cSuper duper,\" transcontinental\nspeedways have no place in the pro\ngram. Engineers say they are still\nin the pipe dream stage. Federal\nand state highway officials generally\nagree there is too little transcon\ntinental motor travel to warrant the\nenormous cost of building such\nroutes.\nSpeeds\nOn urban sections of the inter\nstate system the \u201cdesirable'' speed\nwill be .50 miles an hour and the\nminimum 40 miles an hour.\nOn flat rural sections \u201cdesirable\u201d\nspeed will be 70 and minimum at\nleast 60.\nIn rolling rural country \u201cdesir\nable\u2019 speed will be 60 and minimum\n50. In mountainous country 'desir\nable\u201d speed will be 50 and mini\nmum 40.\nCongress for the first time has\nearmarked federal funds for use in\nurban areas\u2014ll2s,ooo,ooo a year for\nthree years. An additional 5\u201925.-\n000.000 is authorized annually for\nthe federal-aid system, rural and\nurban, during the three-year period.\nCOAL STRIKE ENDS\nSTEEL MILL JOBS\nSharp Cutbacks Coming This\nWeek as 200,000 Miners\nRefuse to Work More\nThan 900 Mines Closed\nPittsburg, Oct. 13\u2014(API\u2014Dwindling\ncoal stockpiles today headed the step!\nindustry into a week of sharp pro\nduction cutbacks as more than half\nof the nation's 400.000 bituminous\nminers were idle in the still-spread\ning mine sti ikes.\nStructural steel and rails for rail\nroads will be chiefly affected, industry\nleaders said, and production of pipe\nand flat steel for automobiles and\nrefrigerators is threatened.\nMore than 900 mines in six states\nare closed over demands of mine\nbosses for recognition of their United\nMine Workers District 50, United\nClerical. Technical and Supervisory\nEmployes. The shutdowns are cost\ning an estimated million tons of coal\ndaily.\nOf the nation's 201.000 Idle miners,\n61.000 are in Pennsylvania. 91.000 in\nWest Virginia, 27,000 In Kentucky.\n3000 each In Ohio \u00abnd Tennessee and\n6000 In Indiana.\nPittsburg district's steel production\nis expected to drop 15 per cent next\nweek, operating at 47 per cent of\ntheoretical capacity, with at least\n10,000 workers being laid off. Individ\nual company, reductions will hit\ndeeper.\nBill Would Make Unions\nResponsible in Contracts\nWashington. Oct 11\u2014< APl\u2014Legis\nlation to make labor unions \"mutual\nly responsible\" with employers for\nkeeping contracts was urged In the\nHouse today by Representative Willis\nRobertson (D-Va)\nHe called for repeal of the Smith-\nConnally sntistrlke act. declaring it\n\"is binding only on employers and\nputs all the responsibilities on the\ncurporations and non* on th* uplona.\"\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, OCTOBER 18, 1945\nMINE OWNERS\nREJECT FIVE\nPEACE PLANS\nU. S. Not to Seize Property\nas Negotiations Are Only\n\u2018Suspended\u2019 Lewis Says\nWorkers \u2018Locked Out\u2019\nAfter Accepting 1 ruce\n|Bi the Associated Press, Oct. 171\nGovernment efforts to halt the\nwidespread bituminous coal strike\ncollapsed last night, Secretary of\nLabor Schwellenbach announced, and\nthe conciliation conference in Wash\nington was postponed indefinitely.\nVo seizure Planned\nSell weler, bach told reporters the\ngovernment would not consider seiz\nure of the struck mines, however,\n\"as long as the negotiations are ad\njourned only subject to call.\"\nJohn L. Lewis. representing the\nUnited Mine Workers, and mine oper\nators had conferred for eight days,\nbut Schwellenbach said he adjourned\nthe meeting after the operators re\njected five separate proposals for set\ntlement.\nLewis told newsmen: \"We are\nlocked out.\u201d\n\"The United Mine Workers have\naccepted every suggestion of the sec\nretary of labor,\u201d he said, adding it\nwas obvious \u201cthat the miners are\nidle because of the obstinacy of the\noperators. The UMW offered to go\nback to work if the operators would\nnegotiate the issues. but the opera\ntors declined.\u201d\n\"I am not going to call them to\ngether again to resume discussions\nuntil there are indications that re\nsumption will be worth while.\u201d the\nlabor secretary said.\nAlso disclosed yesterday in Wash\nington was the War Labor hoard's\nplan to fold up by New Year's day.\nafter spending its last weeks study\ning how to handle reconversion dis\nputes and establish a peacetime wage\npolicy.\nThis was announced by acting\nChairman Lloyd K. Garrison after\na conference with President Truman.\nThe announcement came as the num\nber of persons on strike lines fell to\nabout 385,000, lowest' in weeks. Most\ndisputes are over wage demands.\nOther important labor develop\nments:\n1. AFL longshoremen resumed\nwork and began breaking the tieup\nof 400 shins in New York port, in\nsurgents kept the walkout in force\nalong the Brooklyn waterfront.\nActors Support Union\n2. The strong AFL Screen Actors'\nguild came out in support of motion\npicture industry strikes.\n3. An arbitrator was appointed to\nhead off a threatened AFL strike\nthat would disrupt milk supplies to\n8 000.000 New York area consumers.\n4. AFL gas workers threatened a\nstrike, against a Chicago utility, that\nwould cut oft service to about 1.000,-\n000 customers.\nNAVY IDENTIFIES\nTHREE OF SHIPS\nLOST IN TYPHOON\nAlso Names 30 Others That\nWere Grounded, Three\nDamaged Casualties On\nVarious Ships Withheld\nWashington, Oct. 14 \u2014GAP)\u2014-The\nnavy tonight identified three United\nStates vessels sunk, 30 aground and\nthree others damaged in the Okinawa\ntyphoon Monday and Tuesday.\nThe information was received :\u2122m\nheadquarters of Admiral Nimitz. The\nannouncement did not state whether\nit was a complete list of vessels af\nfected Earlier a navy report said\nISO naval craft were beached or dam-\nThe navy at Pearl Harbor said\ny< tcrday that 28 navy men were\nkilled, 70 missing and 423 injured.\nTie army has announced that 100\nof its personnel were injured.\nShips sunk were rhe Southern Seas\n(not otherwise identified)..LSM (land\nship. medium) 15 and YMS (motor\nminesweeper) 383.\nCa\u00bbualtle\u00ab Not Reported\nThe announcement did not indicate\nthe number of casualties suffered by\nthe various ships. Of those grounded,\nhowever, six had no losses to per\nsonnel.\nShips aground:\nDorsey DM* 1. Southward DMS 10.\nWeehawken CM 12, Industry AMC\n862, Mahogany DM 23, Snowbell AN\n52, Sanandaga AOG 40, Nestor .ARB\n6. Mona Island ARG 9, PGM 5. PGM\n27. PCI 1238, PCI 1239 PC 590. LST\n568, LCM 361. YMS 90. YMS 151. YMS\n176 YMS 193 YMS 275, YMS 296.\nYMS 384. YMS 424. YMS 442. YMS\n454, YP 289, APC 103, APL 14,\nOcelot (IX 10\nDamaged: Tortuga LSD 26, ATR\n58. ATR 75.\nThe following grounded ships re\nport no casualties: Snowbell AN 52,\nNestor ARB 6. APC 103, LSM 361,\nPC 1239 APL 14 and PC 590.\nThis does not imply thai there were\ncasualties aboard all other vessels in\nthe announcement, the navy cau\nticned.\nINHERITANCE STORY\nDOESN\u2019T IMPRESS ARMY\nPfc H. R. Phillips Refuses to\nDiscuss Rich Uncle Tale\nat Camp Kilmer\nCamp Kilmer. N. J.. Oct. 11\u2014(API\nPb. Harold Ray Phillips, self-styled\nheir to a 875,000.000 fortune which\nhe said was willed to him by a Chi\ncago uncle, refused to discuss his\nstow when army public relations\nstun men contacted him today after\na search of almost 24 hours all over\nthis vast post.\nPhillips, who answered a roll call\non time at 1 p. m. (eastern standard\ntime), neither would confirm nor deny\nhis wife's statement that the rich\nuncle never existed.\nArmy officers here have taken no\nofficial cognizant of the soldier's\nstoij; the public relations office said.\nIlir wife, a former WAC who lives\nwith their baby near Springfield. Mo.,\nsaid there that she had talked with\nhim this morning by telephone, but\nshe refused to reveal the conversa\ntion.\nPhillips Is scheduled to fly to Fort\nIjowls Wash., in a da< or two to be\nprocessed.\nThe soldier, a regular army man\nwith eight years\u2019 service told ths\nso,rv about a fortune from an uncle,\nAugustus F. Smith, when he arrived\nin New York Tuesday on the Queen\nElizabeth.\nI Touring Congressmen \u2018Sour\u2019\nOn U. S. Interests Abroad\nJoint Control for Trouble Spots, Change in Russian Re\nlations, Substitute for UNRRA, Suggested\nWashington, Oct. 15 -CAP) \u2014Two\nmore louring congressional commit\ntees returned from Europe today a\nlittle sour on the way American in\nterests abroad are being treated.\nAn 11-man House group under Rep\nresentative Wickersham (D-Okl)\nwhich saw 32 countries reported:\n1. Stress in United States-Russian\nrelations should be placed on points\n\"upon which we ail agree\" rather than\nthose \u201con which we fail to agree.'\n2. America should demand\u2014and get\n\u2014from Russia freedem of movement\nover there as it accords freedom to\nRussians who visit here.\n3. There should be more plain talk\nbetween the United States and Britain\nover trade policies, particularly avia\ntion development and the sterling bloc\ns> stem.\nIt was recommended that the Russo-\nAmerican air be cleared \u201cof suspicion\u201d\nin diplomatic conversations when\nMarshal Zhukov makes his projected i\nvisit here.\nJoint Control Suggested\nAn informal report, touching' on the\nsame situations, was made also in a\nstatement and news conference by\nRepresentatives Mundt (R-SD) and\nStockbridge Woman Fights\nWill of Wealthy N. Y. Aunt\nMrs Yeoli Acton and Six Others Charge Undue Influ\nence by Grenfell Association\nRochester. N. Y., Oct. 15\u2014(API-\nTrial of an action contesting the\n32,500,000 estate of Miss Louie Alice\nHall and alleging undue influence on\nthe part of the Grenfell Association\nof America, residuary legatee, opened\ntoday in Monroe county surrogate's\ncourt.\nKite nephews and two nieces who\nprotested the will also allege undue\ninfluence was exerted by the late Sir\nWilfred and Lady Grenfell and Rob\nert G. Watson, chairman of the board\nof directors of the former Rochester\nTrust and Safe Deposit company.\nWatson and the bank were named\nexecutors of the will.\nThe Grenfell association, a mission-\nEight of His Family Buried\nAs Dazed Soldier Watches\nPvt William Garrett of Kentucky Flown From France\nAfter Auto Crash Wipes Out Family\nMorganfield. Ky., Oct. 11\u2019\nSympathetic neighbors and friends\nnumbering 1000 or more turned out\nthis afternoon as Pvt William H. Gar\nrett stood by in a daze while his en\ntire family\u2014parents and six brothers\nand sisters \u2014was buried in Morgan\nfield's Odd Fellows\u2019 cemetery.\nThe young soldier \u2014he is 23\u2014down\nback bv the army from France to at\ntend the funeral, seemed scarcely to\nknow, what was taking place as Rev-\nLewis Ward Stanger of the Morgan\nfield Baptist church conducted the\nrites.\nThe family was wiped out Saturday\nin an automobile accident near Provi\ndence. Ky. Morganfield friends noti\nfied Senator Alben W. Barkley and\nIf All Nations Used VT\nIt Would Upset Warfare\nBy FRANK CAREY\nWashington. Oct. 11\u2014(AP) \u2014If all\nnations devised a \u201cVT\u201d fuse, a new\nmethod of fighting would have to\nbe invented for any future war.\nThat's the opinion of Gen George\nS. Patton, Jr., who calls the radio\noperated shell exploder the \u201cfunny\nfuse.\u201d\nOne reason is that the VT has\nvirutally eliminated the foxhole or\nthe trench as protection from burst\ning missiles.\nAnother is that VT-fused projec\ntiles need come only within 70 feet\nof an aircraft to do lethal damage.\nVT was developed by American\nscientists with British cooperation. It\ncauses a projectile to burst in the\nair about 70 feet above the ground.\nBefore that, projectiles were fused\neither with \u201ccontact\u201d fuses or \u201ctime\u201d\nfuses.\nA. contact-fused missile must strike\nits objective to be detonated. It is\nvery effective when great explosive\npower is needed at a single point.\nRut as an antipersonnel weapon it\nhas this main disadvantage:\u2014\nWhen the shell or bomb explodes,\nits fragments are hurled upward in\nan Inverted cone. Men hiding in\ntrenches and foxholes or lying flat\non the ground have a good chance of\nescaping injury from the fragments.\nRut the VT-fused missile bursts at\na hlght which sprays the most frag\nments on personnel not under cover.\n\u201cTlme\u201d-fused missiles accomplish\nthe same thing hut each time fuse\ninusi be set differently for targets at\ndiffering range and this takes time\nand care. Moreover, time fuses\nachieve maximum performance only\nwhen the target can he observed.\nThis obviously limits their use at\nnight, during storms or fog.\nWith the VT it makes no difference\nwhether the enemy is lurking high on\na hill or deep in a valley. Th* missile\nTwo-Day \u2018AAF Fair\u2019 at Dayton\nShows Latest Air-War Gadgets\nDayton. O\u201e Oct. 13\u2014(AP)\u2014 Thou\nsands of air-minded war-conscious\nmldweaterners thronged Wright field\ntoday and found an answer to the\nsecret-untll-now of America's mas\ntery of the skies over Germany and\nJapan.\nA two-day \"AAF fair\u201d opened to\nday with the air technical service\ncommand, with headquarters here,\nproudly exhibiting products of Its in\nventive and engineering genius.\nBuzz Bombs. Radio. Radar\nMiles of flag and bunting-bedecked\ntents contained everything from buzz\nbombs to radio and radar, while\noverhead the jet-propelled P-30 made\nUs first public demonstration.\n\"Today\u2019s bombers are but mothers\nand the bombs are her children,\" ex\nplained one gray-halred colonel to a\ngroup gathered around a newly de\nvised 1000 television bomb. \"Mother\nsays \u2019Children, go there, to yonder\ntarget,'\u2014and ths children go!\"\nThe colonel's analogy reduced to\nBolton (R-O) who traveled through 20\nnations during a 63-day trip, repre\nsenting the House Foreign Affairs\ncommittee. I\nThey suggested:\nJoint allied control, instead of one\nnation mandates, in trouble spots.\nCentral administrations for Germany\nand Austria Instead of separate zones.\nGreater dependence on the state\ndepartment staff abroad iu policy\nmaking than \"on pressure groups here\nat home.\"\n\\u -.idciiu.ile substitute\" fog\nUNRRA which \u201cis operating so awk\nwardly cumbersome slow.\"\nMure rapid sale of surplus war\nproperty abroad. Britain is ac\nquiring much of the market.\nAccord the Russians \"as much as\nthey accord us, and no more.\u201d\nQuick solution of the Palestine\nproblem. \"Tense, strained and\ndangerously explosive.\u201d\nThe joint allied control should be\nextended to Palestine. Mundt, said. He\ntold reporters that Britain proposed\nthat the United States \u201ccome in\" at\nthe Potsdam conference but that\nPresident Truman vetoed it.\nary organization, would receive about\n3L400.000 under terms of the will\nThe remainder would be divided\namong other charitable organizations,\nchurches, a hospital and several rela\ntives.\nMiss Hall, who died August 14. 1944,\ninherited the estate of her brothel,\nCharles Hall, inventor of the electro\ntype process for manufacture of\naluminum.\nObjections to the will were filed oy\nMrs Edith S. Paterson of Rochester,\nJames P. Stimson of Syracuse. Louis\nI Stimson of Miami. Fla.. Mrs Yeoli\nS. Acton of Stockbridge. Mass.. John\nIM. Hall of. Pasadena, Cal., George W.\nHall of San Marino, Cal., and Harry\n'm. Hall of West Hartford. Ct.\nRepresentative Earle Clements and\nthe war department immediately made\narrangements to bring the soldier\nsole survivovr of his family back\nfrom France.\nHe crossed the ocean yesterday in\nthe plane which returned Gen Mark\nClark to New York, and was flown\nto Sturgis. Ky., arriving at 12.15 a. m.\ntoday. Two uncles. Marvin Moore of\nHenderson and Willie Moore of Mor\nganfield. are his only* remaining near\nrelatives.\nYoung Garrett had no speculations\ntoday as to his future, except that\nhe had been told he would not re\nturn to France, Whether he is to be\ndischarged soon remains tor army of\nficials to decide.\nwill always explode when it's 70 feet\nabove the objective terrain.\n\u201cEven it we take cover in our fox\nholes.\u201d said a German prisoner cap\ntured in Italy, \u201cwe are not protected\nagainst these deadly shells, since the\nfragments are falling densely and hit\nthe point of impact with an extraor\ndinary power of penetration.* 1\nA prisoner from another area re\nported that two men in his company\nbad been executed \u201cfor refusal to go\non patrol duty, because even diving\ninto ditches did not save troops from\nthe American harassing fire which\ncame at unexpected times and places\nnight and day.\u201d\nI'sed against aircraft, the advan\ntages of the VT fuse are these:\n1. They eliminate 'he necessity of\ntime-fuse setting, with its possibility\nof error.\n2. They don't hurst the shells until\nthey\u2019re in the pay-off area. Other\ntypes of antiaircraft shells often warn\nthe enemy plane he's being fired on,\nand he can take evasive action.\nOur navy says the VT furnished\nsurface ships \u201cwith a devastating re\nply to the airplane.\u201d A report, on\nthe use .of the weapon in defending\nsix destroyers from a torpedo plane\nattack gives this account:\n\"The general impression was that\nthe horizon from the east to the\nnorthwest was full of burning planes.\nThere were too many to count.\nWhether there will be future wars\nto test further the .battle possibilities\nof VT remains to be seen, but keep\nthis in mind:\nThe research that went into the\ndevelopment of those tiny radio sets\nfor the fuses may have important ap\nplications in a world at peace.\nTechnical men already are talking\nabout the possibilities of producing\nradios the size of a matchbox.\nAnd small radios may he designed\nfor lofty flights In stratosphere rock\nets and balloons\u2014to collect meteoro\nlogical data.\nessence the bomb\u2019s operation.\nLaunched aerially. Its flight is eon\ntroled not onlv gyroscopically and by\nperforated tins, but by television and\nradio, enabling a bombardier aboard\nthe mother ship to steer It unerring\nly to the target.\nVisitors seemed amazed at dis\nclosure that visual aiming of some\naerial bombs, either day or night, Is\naided by Slip.ooo candlepower flares In\ntheir tails\u2014housed In metal contain\ners about the size of a pound coffee\ncan.\nOfficers emphasized that although\nthe exhibits presented the cream of\ntechnical genius during the war, the\nvery fact they were being displayed\nbranded them as obsolescent, and\nadded that newer, deadlier engines of\ndestruction had taken their place in\nthe army\u2019s top-secret flies.\nOfficers termed the show bld to\nCongress and the public for funds tn\nmaintain developmental research at\nhigh level.\nU. S. INTENDS\nTO RETAIN ITS\nJAP CONTROL\nByrnes Says Allies Will Be\nAsked to \u2018Advise\u2019 but Not\nShare Rule MacArthur\u2019s\nStatus as Boss of Japan\nWon't Be Altered\nWashington, Oct. 10\u2014(AP)\nCreation of an allied commission to\nadvise on Japanese control policies\nwas announced by Secretary of State\nByrnes today but he emphasized the\nUnited States intends to maintain\nits dominant role.\nThe status of Gen Douglas S. Mac-\nArthur as supreme allied com\nmander in Japan is to remain un\nchanged, Byrnes said, and any time\nthe victor nations fail to agree on\npolicy United States policy will pre\nvail. i\nSoviet Plai^Uiipopiilar*\nRussia has proposed setting up a\ncontrol commission at Tokio, Byrnes\nreported, and while this is yet to be\ntaken up with President Truman and\nthe army and navy, the secretary\nleft no doubt that he favors rejecting\nthe proposal.\nHeadquarters of the advisory com\nmission are to be in 'Washington, with\nmeetings in Tokio when necessary.\nInvitations for the first session here\nthe 23d went x out to nine other na\ntions yesterday.\nThese developments on Japanese\noccupation policy, and machinery' were\ndiscussed by Byrnes at a news con\nference at which he also disclosed:\n1. He has appointed Maj-Gen Frank\nR. McCoy, retired army officer and\npresident of the Foreign Policy- as\nsociation, to be United States repre\nsentative on the far eastern advisory\ncommission.\n2. He has appointed Mark Ethridge,\npublisher of the 'Louisville Courier-\nJournal and Times, to investigate po\nlitical conditions in the Russian-dom\ninated Balkans as the next step in\nAmerican consideration of whether\nto recognize the governments of Ro\nmania and Bulgaria. Byrnes said he\nchose a newsman because he would be\na trained and unprejudiced observer.\n3. The United States, Russia and\nBritain agreed at the big three meet\ning at Berlin to take up separately\nwith Turkey the question of revising\ninternational control of the Darda\nnelles, the straits through which Rus\nsian commerce and naval forces must\nmove from the Black sea to the Medi\nterranean.\n4. Byrnes said he hopes that the\nresignation of Vice-President Juan\nPeron, strong man of the Argentine\ngovernment, may mean better days\nfor the Argentine people.\n5. The United States has not yet\nreceived an answer from Russia on\nits compromise proposal, growing out\nof the stalemated foreign ministers\u2019\nmeeting at London, for a general\nEuropean peace conference by the\nyear end.\n6. Byrnes expressly favors release\nand full publication of decisions made\nat. such conferences as the London\nmeeting and he promised to seek re\nlease where possible of diplomatic\nand other official documents, such as\nthe two-year-old Italian armistice\nterms and the orders under which\nAmerican occupation forces originally\noperated in Germany.\nAAF WOULD KEEP\n6500 PLANES FOR\nPEACETIME FORCE\nHad 65.000 at War Peak\n-600,000 Men Said Needed\nCompared to 2,300,000\nDuring the War\nWashington, Oct. 10 \u2014(AP) The\narmy air force outlined a tentative\npeacetime program\u2014reported to call\nfor 6500 planes and 600,000 men\u2014to\nmembers of the Senate military com\nmittee today.\nThe senators were invited to the\nPentagon building for luncheon and\na \"briefing\u201d by Gen H. H. Arnold,\nchief of the air forces, anti Lieut-\nGen Ira C. Eaker. deputy chief, on\ntheir ideas of what size air force\nshould he maintained in the future.\nThe army' made no announcement\nof the meeting and some of the sena\ntors including acting Chairman\nJohnson (D-Col) \u2014told reporters aft\nerward that they thought the whole\nmatter was \u201coff the record.\" Other\nsenators, however, had not so under\nstood it and related some of the de\ntails of what they were told.\nThese included a planned reduction\nwithin a year or less tn an active\nforce of 6500 planes and 606,000 men\nas compared with a peak wartime\nstrength of 65.000 planes and 2,300,000\nmen.\nSenators said this was described\nas an \"interim force\u201d but that they\ngot the impression It was also the\nair command\u2019s view of the minimum\nneeded in peacetime.\nThe army calls it a \u201c70-group pro\ngram.\u201d An air group corresponds\nroughly to a ground force regiment,\nalthough the number of men may\nvary with the type of planes\u2014heava.\nnu>dium or light bombers, or fighters.\nThe senators also were shown a\nmap designating the peacetime bases\nthe air forces propose to retain.\nThis showed Eglin field In Florida\nas the AAF center. It was explained\nthat ranges and testing equipment\nare permanent Installations there. As\nbefore the war. Maxwell field in Ala\nbama was listed as the air force\ntactical school.\n7013 SHIPS REPAIRED\nAT PEARL HARBOR YARD\nNavy Reveals What Hap\npened at Big Base After the\nWar Started There\nPearl Harbor, Oct 10\u2014(AP> \u2014The\nnavy today took the wraps oft activ\nity at Pearl Harbor navy yard, where\nthe war started. The navy yard re\npaired 7013 ships during the war.\nMore than 2400 of them were In dry\ndock.\nLast January was the busiest\nmonth. Three hundred and forty-two\nvessels were under repair In prepara\ntion directly for the Iwo invasion and\nindirectly for the Okinawa campaign.\nVeritable miracles were performed\nthere\u2014such as the repair of the bat\ntleship Colorado In time for the In\nvasion of the Marianas. Rehearsing\nfor the landing* on Saipan and Ti\nnian. she ripped a hole over a third\nthe length of her hull on an un\ncharted reef.\nPressure Grows at\nFor New U. S. Wage Policy\nEconomists at Washington Believe 15 Per Cent Boost\nOnly Way to End Labor Unrest\nI'\"\nWORK STOPPAGES\nCHILL OPTIMISM\nON RECONVERSION\nProgress Still Considered\nGood but Union Requests\nfor Strike Votes May Dou\nble September Mark\nWashington, Oct. 13\u2014(AP) \u2014Two\nmonths after the peace. Washing\nton's warm optimism over reconver\nsion has chilled in many official quar\nters because of strikes and work\nstoppages in basic industries.\nObjective of the first month fol\nlowing Japanese surrender was civil\nian production starting and spurting\nahead of schedule.\nKeynote of the second month\nwhich ends tomorrow \u2014was produc\ntion crippled in big segments of the\ncoal. oil. steel and lumber industries,\nand threats of stoppages in autos,\ntrucking, shipping and others.\nReconversion progress still was\nconsidered good, in terms of getting\nwar debris out of factories and set\nting them up for output of things\nthat boost the nation's living stand\nard.\nBut today the government reported\nthat requests for strike votes from\nunions would soar to about 600 in\nOctober, nearly double September's\nrecord-breaking tally of 307.\nMeanwhile the administration had\nfailed in its first big test .of persua\nsion to settle strike cases. It re\nsorted to the wartime expedient of\nseizing 50-odd refineries in 15 states\nto get oil and gas flowing.\nAnd government officials discussed,\nbut did not act upon, a proposed re\nvision of its wage-price policy to\ncope with labor's nationwide outcry\nfor 30 per cent higher wages to off\nset loss of wartime earnings.\nBusiness leaders still spoke with\noptimism of expansion and coming\nhigh employment. In one big sur\nvey only 10 large cities saw no\nchance of rehiring all their laid-off\nworkers.\nGovernment went ahead, too, with\nwhat it calls \"de-control.\u201d or knock\ning the wartime shackles off the\neconomy. On Monday these curbs\ngo out the window:\n1. The ban on construction of new\nhomes, stores, offices and hotel build\nings. and public works: also, the\nprice lid on new dwellings.\n2. All remaining priorities on air\nplane passenger travel. Yei the new\nmood of caution was reflected in\nmost of these developments of the\nsecond peacetime month:\u2014\nRations: The government moved\nwarily.\nMeat rationing probably will con\ntinue after November 1; shoes will go\noff the list, then only if production\njumps as it failed to do in Septem\nber; sugar outlook unchanged.\nPrices: The government Jield the\nline.\nOPA clung to its policy of bring\ning new washers, ironers and other\nlong-sought gadgets back at 1942\nprices. Radios\u20143,soo,ooo of them by\nChristmas \u2014will reach the consumer\nat that price level.\nWages: The government, stood pat.\nPresident Truman reaffirmed his\npolicy of allowing general wage\nboosts only where no price increase\nresults.\nBut aids of Reconversion Director\nJohn W. Snyder pressed him to de\nclare for a 10 to 15 per cent increase.\nThey say it would rush prices up\nonly 2or 2 1 per cent, that reconver\nsion\u2019 can be speeded if the govern\nment takes the lead instead of let\nting unions and management fight it\nout on the picket lines. Snyder has\nnot. budged.\nGoods:\u2014\nRefrigerations, washers and radios\nbegan to appear as dealers' samples.\nMost major auto makers were in or\nnear production. Textiles improved,\nhut officials began to investigate\nwhy more low-cost garments bad\nfailed to show up.\nJobs: The government tfas en\ncouraged.\nUnemployment climbed above the\n2,000,000 mark, but 700.000 jobs were\ngoing begging as laid-off workers\nshopped around. About one-third of\nthose discharged did not seek job\nless pay.\nYet ihe government warned that\nhigh unemployment will persist\nthrough 1946 because industrv can\nnot expand fast enough to keep up\nwith army and navy discharges. In\ndustry\u2019 people say many war workers\napparently' have dropped out. of the\nlabor market, but may come back\nlater.\nPEACETIME TRAINING\nPROGRAM OFFERED\nSenator Knowland Sets Up\nPoint System Giving Mili\ntary Credit for Continuing\nin School\nWashington. Oct. 11 (AP) A\npeacetime universal military training\nprogram designed to meet objections\nthnt training would Interfere with\nyoung men's schooling was proposed\ntoday by Senator Knowland (R-Cal).\nHe introduced legislation to set up\na point system whereby youngsters\ncould. If they desired, get credit for\na year's military training while con\ntinuing in school.\nIt would:\n1. Continue registration for military\ntraining of boys upon reaching age\n2. Direct that upon reaching age 21\nthey .muot undergo a year of military\ntraining unless they had accumulated\nmeantime. 36 points for military\ntraining.\n3. Award points at the rate of nine\na year for military training in edu\nrational institutions' reserve officers\ntraining corps, the National guard,\noi* In organized reserves.\nThus, by starting soon enough, n\nyoungster could accumulate 36 points\nand discharge bls obligation as to\nmilitary training before reaching 21.\nFor the benefit of those now in the\narmed services, the legislation also\ncontains a provision that service In\nthe army and navy shall count as\nthree points a month.\nM\u2019Nutt\u2019s Aide Confirmed\nAs FSA Administrator\nWashington. Oct. 11\u2014<AP)\u2014Watson\nR. Miller of Maryland was confirmed\nby the Senate today as federal secur\nity administrator. He succeeds Paul\nV. McNutt, who has been appointed\nhigh commissioner to the Philippine.*.\nMiller has been serving as assistant\nadministrator to McNutt.\nNATIONAL\nWashington, Oct 10\u2014(AP)\u2014Re\nconversion Director John W. Snyder\nwas under Increasing pressure today\nto declare a new government wage\nprice policy promptly to stem the\ntide of labor unrest.\nTwo officials of the Office of War\nMobilization and Reconversion, who\nrequested that their names not ba\npublished, disclosed that economists\nand advisers in that agency are al\nmost unanimous in the belief that\naction by Snyder or President Tru-\nman is imperative.\nThey hold that a wage increase of\nabout 15 per cent, on the average,\ncould be allowed with no appreciable\ninflationary effect on price levels.\nThey argue that the general level\nof factory wages would rise about\nthat much\u2014perhaps higher\u2014if the Is\nsue were bargained out by unions and\nemployers or battled out on the pick\net lines.\nBut meantime, they say. the return\nto high output of civilian goods would\nbe slowed by more work stoppages,\nwhich might be avoided if the gov\nernment took leadership in providing\na wage-price pattern.\nA government declaration would\ncarry the assurance that employers\ncould promptly get OPA\u2019s considera\ntion of price increases to cover their\nwage boosts up to the 15 per cent sr\nother prescribed level. For wage, in\ncreases beyond that point, thers\nwould be no assurance of price re\nlief.\nIn the opinion of government econ\nomists. an average increase of 15 per\ncent would increase prices around 2\nor 2'2 per cent\u2014a supposedly \"safe\u201d\nrise in living costs.\nAlthough interviewed separately,\nboth OWMR informants asked that\ntheir names be withheld. One believed\nSnyder would stick to the administra\ntion\u2019s \u201chands-off\u201d policy, the other\nheld that the pressure inside and out\nside the government would prove ir\nresistible.\n\"We cannot go through reconver\nsion sitting on the wage lid,\u201d one of\nthe officials said. This source, high in\nthe reconversion command, admitted\nthere was \u201cmuch commotion aniHteon\nfusion\u201d in the government on the\nissue, brought to a head by ClO\u2019s\ndemand for a 30 per cent wage rise.\nPresident Truman recently indi\ncated he was not ready for a change\nin the existing hold-the-line program.\nHe told his news conference last week v\nthe government has a definite wage\npolicy. He read the \u201cV-J\u201d wage or\nder issued by him August 18. In gen\neral it bars any wage Increases which\nmean prices must be increased. How\never, the order also says raises can\nbe- granted to correct \u201cinequities\u201d\u2014\nwithout explalinng that word\u2014even if\nprice increases would result.\n\u2018FEW SELFISH MEN\u2019\nWILL NOT PREVAIL,\nTRUMANDECLARES\nPresident Returns to Wasb\ntington From Middle West\nAfter Blasting Industrial\nTroublemakers\nWashington, Oct. 10\u2014(AP)\u2014Presi\ndent Truman returned to the White\nHouse tonight after winding up a five\nday Middle West trip with an im\npromptu blast at \u201ca few selfish men.\u201d\nSpeaking extemporaneously at the\nend of a prepared speech dedicating\na Tennessee Valley authority dam,\nthe President said some men place\nselfish interests above the public wel\nfare.\nWithout naming them, be declared\nthey\u2019 would not prevail.\nThen he went to Paducah and\nboarded his plane for Washington ar\nriving here at 5.38 p. m. after a three\nhour flight.\nMrs Truman and their daughter,\nMargaret, met the President and his\npaiAy at the airport-\nIn his Gilbertsville speech, Mr Tru-r\nman called for development of other\ngreat river valleys.\nHe said the country was having\n\"our little troubles now, a few of\nthem\" which he said were not serious\nbut \u201cjust a blowup after th* letdown\nfrom war\u201d with people still letting\noff steam from the strains of war.\n\"And we still have a tew selfish\nmen who,think more of their personal\ninterests than they do of the publi\u00ab\nwelfare,\u201d he added.\n\"But they are not going to prevail.\nYou are not. going to let them pre\nvail. You are going to force every,\nbody to get into this harness and\npush and pull and pull until that\ngreat age 1 am prophesying cornea\nabout.\u201d\nSpeaking under a hot sun at the\nbase of the JI 1.5,000,000 Kentucky dam\nbefore several thousand, the President\ncontinued:\n\"Now' let'^ all go home and go to\nwork. Cut out the foolishness and\nmake this country what it ought to\nbe th< greatest nation th\u00ab> sun has\never shown upon,'*\nM\u2019KEOUGH IS GIVEN\nSENATE APPROVAL\nFormer CIO-PAC Campaign\ner Gets Six-Year Term On\nMaritime Commission After\nCapitol Dispute\nWashington. Oct. 11\u2014(AP)\u2014By an\neight-vote margin, the Senate today\nupheld President Truman's appoint\nment of Raymond S. MeKeough for\na six-year term on the United Stateq\nMaritime commission.\nThe vote for confirmation was 42\nto 34. it came after a sharp debate\nrevolving about MeKeough'* connec\ntions with the CIO-PAC. No opponent\nquestioned his ability or character.\nA former Democratic member of\nthe House from Chicago, MeKeough\ndirected the ClO-PAC's campaign in\nIllinois, Wisconsin and Indiana last\nyear for A fourth term tor President\nRoosevelt.\nMeKeough'* nomination was the\nfirst Truman appointment to raise a\nmajor controversy at the Capitol.\nSenator Overton (D-La.), chairman\nof a commerce subcommittee which\nvoled against confirmation, led the\nopposition to MeKeough. He told th*\nSenate that approval of MeKeough\nmight \u201clight the fuse that may blow\nup a powderkeg\" in maritime labor\nrelations.\nThis was a reference to rivalry be\ntween the CIO and AFL maritime\nunions. \"We must do everything In\nour power to avoid a general strike\nof seamen,\" Overton declared.","height":"26071","width":"19583"}}
